@* LINQ ordering + paging over a List (BENCH n°45, decision 126): OrderBy/OrderByDescending sort a COPY by a
   numeric key selector -> `[...arr].sort((__a,__b) => key(__a) - key(__b))` (JS sort is stable, like LINQ's
   OrderBy); Skip/Take are `.slice(n)` / `.slice(0,n)`; First/Last terminate the sequence in a scalar. Over
   [3,7,2,9,5]: `OrderBy(x=>x).Skip(1).First()` = sorted [2,3,5,7,9], drop first -> [3,5,7,9], take first = 3;
   `OrderByDescending(x=>x).Take(2).Last()` = sorted desc [9,7,5,3,2], take two -> [9,7], last = 7. So #lo -> "3"
   and #hi -> "7", exactly as Blazor runs the same LINQ. lo/hi are read by the template AND assigned in Go -> signals;
   _nums is an immutable literal list. No @using System.Linq (it would be refused; LINQ resolves via ImplicitUsings). *@

<p>Lo: <span id="lo">@lo</span>, Hi: <span id="hi">@hi</span></p>

<button id="go" @onclick="Go">go</button>

@code {
    private List<int> _nums = new List<int> { 3, 7, 2, 9, 5 };
    private int lo = 0;
    private int hi = 0;

    private void Go()
    {
        lo = _nums.OrderBy(x => x).Skip(1).First();
        hi = _nums.OrderByDescending(x => x).Take(2).Last();
    }
}
